  "verdict": "CONTROL WORKS -- BUT ONLY WITH A SUBSAMPLING-ROBUST ESTIMATOR; Sec 14.1 must specify one. The control CONCEPT is sound: with the true sigma known (oracle) the residual confound is 27% of the identity reference, down from the no-control 38% mean / 70% worst cell; and with cleanly separated avalanches (N_aval=40) a standard ratio estimator attains 24% with perfect discrimination (certification power 1.00). But on the physiological observable -- a single short continuous SUBSAMPLED stream (T_obs=250, f=0.5) -- the NAIVE lag-1 slope is attenuated toward zero (true sigma=0.94 -> sigma_hat=0.79), the DANGEROUS direction: it false-certifies 79% of confounded near-critical systems as safe, so the residual confound only reaches 35% and discrimination collapses (certification power 0.21). This is the known subsampling bias (Wilting & Priesemann 2018). The subsampling-robust multistep-regression (MR) estimator on the SAME short trace removes the attenuation (true sigma=0.94 -> sigma_MR=0.92) and RESTORES the control: residual confound 29% of reference, accepting 90% of genuinely sub-critical systems and rejecting 83% of confounded ones (certification power 0.75). Honest close: the \u00a714.1 control is executable and recovers M_diss's power, PROVIDED the distance-to-criticality is measured with a subsampling-robust estimator (MR-type) or from cleanly segmented avalanches -- NOT the naive slope, which fails in the dangerous direction. The paper must name this estimator requirement; with it, the loop closes.",
